1.1.1/1.452.217/841.122.965 = 2.5 KB
Here's another synapse nearby!

1.1.1/1.452.217/841.122.966 = 2.5 KB
Hello World!

1.1.1/1.452.217/841.122.967 = 2.5 KB
And another!

1.1.1/1.500.500/500.500.500 = 2.5 KB
A deeper synapse at the midway.

1.1.1/1.999.999/999.999.999 = 4.9 KB
the very last synapse!

So, on average, opening a synapse space requires 2.5 KB of overhead. This is about 1 or 2 protein's worth of information.

Now, let's see what happens when we combine these documents with phext! Neighbors encode more efficiently - the closer a node is to another node, the less space we require. We can encode 3 nodes in 2.5 KB of space if they are very close. So phext scales nicely with our physical model.

The reference nodes above require 10 KB of space uncompressed, but only 897 bytes compressed or 323 bytes when compressed after merging via phext.